# üêû bug report

### Description

When you have an `<img>` inside a `<noscript>`, the `<img>` still triggers a request.

My need for proper behavior of `<noscript>` is for lazy loading of images. In the event that JavaScript isn't available, you [put the image in a `<noscript>`](https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/performance/lazy-loading-guidance/images-and-video/#javascript_availability) (which works in Angular using server-side rendering). However, if `<noscript>` still loads the image in Angular, that ruins the point of lazy loading.

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction

https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-issue-repro2-r3jwsk

